text: You know, that's really funny because it happened on my very first day of work at the hedge fund. But really, it took me like many years to figure out what it actually means. And the thing is that when you start off as a quant, your temptation is to take like every piece of data you can find and shove it into your model because you don't have like any judgment or any understanding of really how things work. So you're just trying to replace it. Like what you're trying to do often is build an exact replica of the real world. So like you might want to say, hey, who are all the holders of a particular position? So you can look at something like Apple. Apple, you know, you can go through all the 13D filings and ETF daily reports and mutual fund data. And Swiss National Bank owns a bunch of Apple shares and there's employee ownership. So you can build an imperfect but directionally pretty accurate map of who all the shareholders are. Now, even if you have like perfect. Perfect data, that's actually a lot less useful than you would think because it doesn't really tell you why somebody owns the shares and more importantly, what they might do if things change. And really like that's the most important thing because it's the marginal flow that sets the price. Think about that you or I, we have a hundred bucks in our checking account and we decide, hey, we're going to buy the S&P 500 index fund. So give our money to Vanguard or BlackRock, whoever. And they take that hundred bucks. And out of that, seven of it goes towards Apple shares. So they need to find somebody else who currently holds Apple and is willing to let go of it in exchange for cash. And then when you redeem out, that process happens in reverse where somebody ends up with the Apple shares and takes the cash. So it's much more important rather than having mapping reality exactly to have, even if you have a much more simpler model, but that incorporates how things might change. And I think that's, I think that's a great way to start to think about what's going to change in the future. Even if you're not going to be exact at all, but directionally, if different events happen, what are the flow impacts they're going to cause? And the way I think about it is like, imagine you take an airplane and you fly over Los Angeles or any other big city. So you can see all the cars on the ground and some of those cars that are going to be in parking lots or driveways or on the road or on freeways. But really like that's just a snapshot of where all these cars are. And if you take the same picture a few hours later, it's going to look completely different. So really it's much, much more about building a model of how things will evolve and change rather than knowing exactly where everything is right now. And particularly in markets, like you don't really want to know like where is there traffic right now? It's much more about like where is there traffic going to be?
